- VSCode Version: 1.7.0 / 1.7.1 / 1.8.0
- OS Version: macOS Sierra / Windows

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Open any .php file
2. Insert &lt;script&gt;&lt;?php ?&gt;&lt;/script&gt; anywhere
3. The syntax highlighting for the rest of the .php code breaks

Description:

We have a lot of .php files containing HTML and sometimes &lt;script&gt; tags with PHP variables inside them. If the PHP variable is echoed in one line inside the &lt;script&gt;, like &lt;script&gt;&lt;?php echo $var; ?&gt;&lt;/script&gt;, the syntax highlighting breaks for the rest of the PHP code after that line. 
However, it seems to work if you move the closing ?&gt; tag inside the &lt;script&gt; on a new line. It also works fine on VS Code 1.6.1.

Example:

&lt;?php 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;echo $test; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// syntax highlighting ok 
?&gt; 
&lt;script&gt; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;?php echo $test; ?&gt; 
&lt;/script&gt; 
&lt;?php 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;echo $test; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// syntax highlighting broken 
?&gt;

